[[[break]]]added at line 0: *lime {code *green I found this in the 31 March edition of Time Magazine whilst stuck at Sydney airport. It suggests that Kuhn has penetrated the scientific subconscious more than we might suspect.

Title: Cosmic Flock. The solar system is filled with NASA's busy ships - and they're having a very good year
- Dan Cray

...'All three missions have thrilled and surprised scientists - who pride themselves on knowing more or less what to expect. "I sit back with my mouth open, watching paradigms shift," says Linda Spilker, Cassini's deputy project scientist'

My questions - how many paradigms have, in fact, shifted? How do we define a paradigm shift in an obscure field that we do not know anything about? What qualifies as a paradigm shift? 

The biggest paradigm shifts that we recognise, such as the overhaul of Newtonian mechanics with quantum mechanics, have involved a change in the fundamental questions that you are allowed to ask within the paradigm. Is it a paradigm shift, or simply a scientific advance, when new insights allow you to answer the original questions in a different way? Should a paradigm shift be confined to the scientific community in which it was defined?

Any thoughts?

Melanie

p.s. - how do you 'watch paradigm shifts', and does this require a gaping mouth?? Interesting journalism...*
}*